  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Dragon Repository Temple
  author: Ko Dun-gyeom
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A solitary peak gleams like jade, supreme and perfect,
    A newly built pavilion rises against the azure sky.
    Within the clarity of emptied ravines,
    Misty clouds trail their gossamer veils.
    After snow, visitors ascend to a realm of silver,
    Beneath the moon, souls rest in palaces of crystal.
    The master sits in thoughtless meditation,
    While beyond the railings, the wind sighs through ten thousand hollows.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Dragon Repository Temple (龍藏寺) is a Buddhist monastery; the poem celebrates both its architectural beauty and spiritual significance.
  - key: ''
    value: The imagery of 'silver' and 'crystal' palace evoke Buddhist cosmology and the transcendent beauty perceived through spiritual practice.
  - key: ''
    value: The final image of wind through 'ten thousand hollows' suggests the presence of the divine permeating all natural forms, a common motif in East Asian Buddhist poetry.
